<DOC><DOCNO> AP880613-0261 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0735EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-13 0536</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0558</SECOND><DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   OPEC members have recessed their midyearconference until Tuesday so the 13-nation cartel's oil ministerscould informally discuss disagreements over a proposed new quota inproduction.   The conference opened Saturday and was recessed after Sunday'smeeting until Tuesday morning. Afterwards, two Arab oil ministersleft, with one expected to return by Tuesday but the other sayinghe might not.   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries ministers havebeen considering whether to change an existing agreement among 12of the members that limits the cartel's oil output to 15.06 millionbarrels a day.   That quota, which was extended in December and expires June 30,was aimed at supporting oil prices at $18 a barrel but prices havebeen well below that.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Despite the biggest increase in food costssince January, wholesale prices rose a moderate 0.5 percent in May,the government said.   The report, issued Friday, supported beliefs that inflation isaccelerating but not dangerously. The rise in the LaborDepartment's producer price index for finished goods in May washalfway between a 0.4 percent increase in April and a 0.6 percentjump in March.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texas investor Robert M. Bass succeeded inderailing Macmillan Inc.'s restructuring plan when a state judge inDelaware ordered the publishing giant to refrain from paying aspecial dividend.   Jack B. Jacobs, a judge in Chancery Court in Wilmington, Del.,issued a temporary restraining order Friday preventing Macmillanfrom paying the $52.35-a-share dividend, which was to be the firstphase in a restructuring plan that also included splitting thecompany in two.   A group led by Bass has offered $1.9 billon for Macmillan, whoseboard rejected it as inadequate.  </TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An investment group's $2.8 billion cash bid totake over Centel Corp. still stands, despite rejection by thecompany's chairman.   The investment group led by Asher B. Edelman and George L.Lindemann had set a June 10 deadline in a letter announcing theirbid late last month.   Centel Chairman John P. Frazee Jr. dismissed the offer when itwas received May 31 and has not reconsidered, spokesman Bill Whitesaid Friday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn said he wasforming a new holding company to act as his sole vehicle foracquisitions, including a possible hostile takeover bid for TexacoInc.   Icahn, Texaco's biggest shareholder, said Friday the holdingcompany intended to raise up to $3.25 billion through an offeringof $500 million to $750 million in common stock and about $2.5billion in debt securities.   The Icahn group of companies also will contribute equity to theholding company, including its interests in Texaco and Trans WorldAirlines Inc.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former top Western Union Corp. executiveset up a network of ``double agents'' to establish a rival to thetroubled telecommunications company and used his position to stealLatin American business from it, Western Union charges.   But a lawyer for the executive, John Lanzelotti of Port Reading,N.J., said Friday the suit was in retaliation for fee and expenseclaims by Latin American agent companies, and denied the charges.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>